Nov 30 2008 	Quirky beginning to show its age but can be a good value	This was my first time at Carriage House. I bit on a $69 rate over the Thanksgiving weekend after seeing the overall excellent reviews of this property.Carriage House is certainly reasonable at a low rate such as $69, but there were some quirks and the hotel is somewhat dated.Although the word &quot;suite&quot; is often thrown around to describe CH rooms, they're essentially standard size hotel rooms with a kitchenette (and no counter or seating associated with the tiny kitchenette either). Bathrooms are standard tub/shower combination; in my room, the drain was super slow and I needed to have the property come fix both the drain and the shower head, which was of an annoying needle-spray type. While the property did fix both issues, the slow drain should have been picked up by housekeeping or via the hotel's room PM process - it's not something a guest should have to report. The room is a late 80s vintage, with blond woods, floral print bedspreads and almond fixtures. The AC in the room was loud and loved to kick on obnoxiously, run for 2-3 minutes, then kick off with a loud sigh. Watching TV during an AC cycle meant constantly turning up and down the TV volume to compensate. When the AC was off there was definite noise from traffic and the monorail on the south side of the building. These days, Carriage House is virtually encased on all sides by large high rise condo buildings, so there is no real view from any room.TVs have been updated to flat panels, but there is no HD content available, and the TVs are recessed too far inside the armoire &quot;hole&quot; to allow for reasonable viewing from anywhere other than the bed.Hallways are low-ceilinged with old style drop ceilings, leading to a claustrophobic atmosphere.Most annoying was the inability to connect to the room's wired internet access. While many wireless signals (for a fee) were easily acquired, the hotel's system seems finicky on certain laptops such as ThinkPads. The hotel responded to my complaint by bringing up one of their HP laptops, connecting successfully, and then washing their hands of the issue by directing me to the wired internet provider. Two phone calls and 25 minutes on hold later, the CSR claimed their &quot;keyboard wasn't working&quot; and could I please call back later. I ended up paying an additional $12 to connect via one of the wireless providers.Given the overall value proposition, at $69 weekends this property can still be a reasonable choice. I think for future Vegas weekends I would likely pay $10 or even $20 more to stay at other choices, including Bill's and various Marriott/Hilton/HIExpress options.	
